## Code Style Guidelines

### General
- Use early returns for better code readability
- Follow DRY (Don't Repeat Yourself) principle
- Write self-documenting code with clear variable and function names
- Keep functions small and focused on single responsibility
- Use proper error handling with try-catch blocks
- Follow Vue 2 Options API patterns

### Naming Conventions
- Use camelCase for variables and functions
- Use PascalCase for components
- Prefix event handlers with 'handle' (e.g., handleClick, handleSubmit)
- Use descriptive names that explain purpose
- Avoid abbreviations unless widely accepted
- Component names should be multi-word (e.g., UserProfile, DataTable)

### JavaScript
- Use ES6+ features where supported
- Implement proper error handling
- Use async/await for asynchronous operations
- Follow functional programming principles
- Use proper type checking
- Implement proper logging

### Styling
- Use Vuetify components and classes
- Follow BEM naming for custom CSS
- Use scoped styles in components
- Implement responsive design
- Use CSS variables for theme values
- Keep styles modular and reusable

### Accessibility
- Implement proper ARIA attributes
- Ensure keyboard navigation
- Add proper focus management
- Include alt text for images
- Use semantic HTML elements
- Follow WCAG 2.1 guidelines

### Performance
- Use v-if and v-show appropriately
- Implement proper list rendering with :key
- Use computed properties for complex calculations
- Implement proper caching strategies
- Optimize images and assets
- Use proper lazy loading

### Testing
- Write unit tests for components
- Use Vue Test Utils
- Implement proper test coverage
- Follow testing best practices
- Document test cases
- Use proper mocking

### Git
- Write clear commit messages
- Follow conventional commits
- Keep commits atomic
- Review code before committing
- Use proper branching strategy
- Keep feature branches up to date

